---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { SITE } from '../../lib/site';
import { hreflangAlternates } from '../../lib/hreflang';

const title = 'Our Charter - How MadDoktor2 Tests & Writes';
const description =
  'The editorial charter of MadDoktor2: how we research, test and write our malware-removal and PC-security guides - honesty first, no fearmongering, no fake claims, and clear affiliate disclosure.';

const schema = [
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'Article',
    headline: 'MadDoktor2 Editorial Charter',
    description,
    inLanguage: 'en',
    datePublished: '2026-06-22',
    dateModified: '2026-06-22',
    author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: SITE.name, url: SITE.url },
    publisher: { '@id': `${SITE.url}/#org` },
    mainEntityOfPage: `${SITE.url}/charter/`,
  },
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
    itemListElement: [
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: SITE.url },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Charter', item: `${SITE.url}/charter/` },
    ],
  },
];

const alternates = hreflangAlternates('/charter/');
---

<Base {title} {description} {schema} lang="en" {alternates} canonicalPath="/charter/">
  <article class="prose rise mx-auto">
    <p class="mono text-xs text-ink-faint">~ / charter</p>
    <h1 class="mt-4 font-mono text-2xl font-semibold text-ink sm:text-3xl">
      Our charter - how we test &amp; write
    </h1>

    <p class="mt-6 text-lg text-ink-dim">
      MadDoktor2 is an independent resource for malware removal, anti-spyware and PC security and
      privacy. This charter is the set of rules we hold ourselves to. If a guide here ever breaks one
      of them, it's a bug - tell us on the <a href="/contact/">contact page</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>1. Honesty before clicks</h2>
    <p>
      We never invent statistics, test results, lab benchmarks, awards or user numbers. We don't claim
      to have personally tested software we haven't, and we don't dress up vendor marketing as our own
      findings. When we cite a number or a claim, it comes from a named, checkable source.
    </p>

    <h2>2. No fearmongering</h2>
    <p>
      Security writing is full of scare tactics designed to push a purchase. We don't do that. We
      explain what a threat actually is, how likely it is to affect you, what genuinely helps, and -
      just as important - what does <em>not</em> help. A free, built-in tool that solves your problem
      is a better answer than an expensive suite you don't need.
    </p>

    <h2>3. Clear, useful steps</h2>
    <p>
      Every removal guide aims to be something you can actually follow on a real, possibly infected,
      Windows PC: what the symptom looks like, which tool to use, the exact steps, and how to confirm
      the machine is clean afterwards. We state the limits of each method plainly.
    </p>

    <h2>4. Affiliate transparency</h2>
    <p>
      Some links on this site are affiliate links, which means we may earn a commission at no extra
      cost to you. We only recommend tools we'd be comfortable using ourselves, affiliate or not, and
      we mark sponsored links clearly. Read the full
      <a href="/affiliate-disclosure/">affiliate disclosure</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>5. Independence</h2>
    <p>
      MadDoktor2 is run independently. We are not the old discussion forum or community that once used
      this domain, and we don't claim any affiliation with it - see the
      <a href="/heritage/">heritage page</a> for the honest history. Our recommendations are not paid
      placements: a vendor cannot buy a better rating here.
    </p>

    <h2>6. Privacy of our own readers</h2>
    <p>
      We practice what we write about. Analytics load only after you accept, IPs are anonymised, and
      we collect no more than we need. See our <a href="/privacy-policy/">privacy policy</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
